data.value:
A declaration command prints the declaration of all wires contained in the given modules header
Command can be used like the following examples: d d -c0 d -d0 -c1
Available Modifiers: -d0 : Will not include direction comments ignoring default settings -d1 : Will include direction comments ignoring default settings ignoring default settings -c0 : Will not include the comments contained in the input header ignoring default settings -c1 : Will include the comments contained in the input header ignoring default settings
Example =================================== Input: module my_module #( parameter paramOne = 1, parameter paramTwo = 2 )( input wire myInput, output wire [7:0] myOutBus );
Creates: wire myInput; wire [7:0] myOutBus;

A instatntiation will create the syntax needed to instantiate a module that is given as input.
Command can be used like the following examples: i i -e1 i -e1 -d0 -c1
Available Modifiers: -s0 : Will Create empty signal assignments ignoring default settings (e.g. .paramOne(paramOne) becomes .paramOne()) -s1 : Will Create filled signal assignments with same name ignoring default settings (e.g. .paramOne(paramOne)) -d0 : Will not include direction comments ignoring default settings -d1 : Will include direction comments ignoring default settings ignoring default settings -c0 : Will not include the comments contained in the input header ignoring default settings -c1 : Will include the comments contained in the input header ignoring default settings
Example =================================== Input: module my_module #( parameter paramOne = 1, parameter paramTwo = 2 )( input wire myInput, output wire [7:0] myOutBus );
Creates: my_moduel #( .paramOne(paramOne), .paramTwo(paramTwo) ) inst_my_moduel ( .myInput(myInput), .myOutBus(myOutBus) );
